{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011eJ4iFzBFG7CSy7fE3qSCc","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 10 ACs have verification tier tags. All are `test-provable` which is correct — crash recovery is verifiable via unit tests with mocked state, no running app needed.\n\n---\n\n**Story created:** `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/5-3-crash-recovery-resume.md`\n\n**Story details:**\n- Story ID: 5.3\n- Story Key: 5-3-crash-recovery-resume\n- Status: ready-for-dev\n- ACs: 10 (all `test-provable`)\n- Tasks: 7\n\n**Key design decisions in the story:**\n- Resume is implicit — presence of checkpoints in `tasks_completed` IS the resume signal, no separate mode flag\n- `isTaskCompleted(state, taskName, storyKey)` does tuple matching on (task_name, story_key)\n- Early exit when `phase: completed` — avoids re-executing finished workflows\n- Loop block resume preserves `iteration` counter and skips completed tasks within the current iteration\n- No changes to the write path (`dispatchTaskWithResult`); only the read-before-dispatch path is added\n\n**Note:** Per your instructions, sprint-status.yaml was NOT modified. No git add/commit performed.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Ambiguity in epic definition:** The epic AC says \"no task executed twice\" but doesn't specify the mechanism. I resolved this by defining tuple-based checkpoint matching `(task_name, story_key)` which is the natural fit given the existing `TaskCheckpoint` shape.\n- **Ambiguity: loop block resume semantics.** The epic AC doesn't specify what happens when a crash occurs mid-loop-iteration. I documented the edge case explicitly (iteration counter must not double-increment on resume) and described the guard logic needed.\n- **AC #8 (memory/leak for 4+ hours):** Tagged `test-provable` because the analysis is structural (verify no event listeners, no unbounded arrays, O(N) growth) rather than requiring a real 4-hour run. A dev can verify this by code inspection + targeted tests. Borderline `runtime-provable` but test-provable is achievable.\n- **Missing `--resume` CLI flag:** The epic mentions `--resume` but that's story 5-4 (Run & Status Commands). This story implements the engine-level resume behavior; the CLI flag is out of scope. Noted in anti-patterns.\n- **No project-context.md found** in the repo. Skipped that section of the workflow.\n- **PRD NFR numbering mismatch:** The PRD uses different NFR numbers than architecture-v2.md. PRD NFR21 (\"Ralph loop must recover from crash\") maps to what architecture calls NFR6-8. Referenced both.\n\n**Risks:**\n- The loop block resume logic (Task 5) is the most complex part. The iteration-increment guard to prevent double-increment on resume requires careful implementation.\n- AC #8 (no memory leaks over 4+ hours) is hard to prove definitively via unit tests. Structural analysis is the pragmatic approach.\n\n**Observations:**\n- The existing codebase already does 90% of what crash recovery needs — state is persisted after every task. This story just adds the \"read and skip\" logic, which is architecturally clean.\n- All 10 ACs are `test-provable` because the entire resume mechanism operates on in-memory state objects that can be pre-populated in tests.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 22\n- By tool: Read: 10, Grep: 6, Bash: 2, Glob: 3, Write: 1, Skill: 0 (skill invocation handled separately)\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `git diff --name-only` (~20 lines), `git log --oneline -5` (~5 lines)\n- Files read: 10 unique, 10 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: None. Each read targeted a specific file/section needed for story context."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a9e8b4b84c16ff141 (use SendMessage with to: 'a9e8b4b84c16ff141' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 66494\ntool_uses: 37\nduration_ms: 242802</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b4a1da7-9e18-4302-ad13-ce7f0aff0314","uuid":"cc529900-cd7a-4809-940f-a1dec09b20a6","timestamp":"2026-04-02T22:46:13.730Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /create-story for story 5-3-crash-recovery-resume. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n\n**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n\nDefault to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surp